title: SpaceX Falcon 9 launches fifth GPS satellite for U.S. Space Force
summary: A SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket on Jan. 18 lifted off at 7:24 a.m. Eastern from Space Launch Complex 40 at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station, Florida, carrying a U.S. Space Force GPS satellite.

title: Reports calls on NASA to improve coordination of Artemis international partnerships
summary: NASA’s inspector general says that the agency needs to do a better job coordinating international partnerships in its Artemis lunar exploration campaign and overcoming obstacles like export control.

title: China to launch relay satellite next year to support moon landing missions
summary: China will launch its Queqiao-2 communications relay satellite in 2024 to support upcoming robotic landing missions at the lunar south pole and far side of the moon.

title: Rocket Lab cautiously optimistic about Neutron’s future in national security launch
summary: Rocket Lab sees the U.S. military as a potential customer of the company’s future medium-lift rocket, Neutron

title: SpaceX launches sixth next-generation GPS satellite
summary: SpaceX launched its fourth mission of the year, a GPS-III satellite for the US Space Force, on Wednesday, Jan. 18. The launch saw a Falcon 9 rocket lift off from Space Launch Complex 40 (SLC-40) at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station at 7:24 EST (12:24 UTC).

title: Spanish startup to upgrade tiny satellites to take on global IoT market
summary: Spanish startup Fossa Systems, which operates a constellation for connecting low-power monitoring devices, hopes to move pilot projects to full-blown commercial services this year by adding more capable satellites to its fleet.

title: Raytheon to develop planning software for military cargo missions that would fly on space rockets
summary: Raytheon won a $8.7 million contract to develop mission planning software for the U.S. Air Force rocket cargo program.

title: U.S. delivers first of two space sensors to be hosted on Japanese satellites
summary: The U.S. Space Force announced Jan. 17 it has delivered the first of two space sensor payloads scheduled to fly on Japan’s navigation satellites.

title: CesiumAstro acquires U.K. startup TXMission
summary: CesiumAstro, an Austin-based startup specializing in phased array technology, has acquired TXMission, a U.K. company that develops software-defined radios and modems.
